<Layout
	title="About Low Hanging Data"
	description="What Low Hanging Data is and why concise, transparent analysis matters."
	pubDate={new Date('March 01 2025')}
	heroImage="/blog-placeholder-about.jpg"
>
	<p>
		<strong>Low Hanging Data</strong> is a project built on a simple conviction: the best data analysis
		is the simplest analysis that answers the question. Before reaching for a model, a complex pipeline,
		or an elaborate visualization, pick the fruit that's already within reach.
	</p>

	<h2>The Three Principles</h2>
	<p>
		Every article and analysis published here is held to three standards:
	</p>
	<ul>
		<li>
			<strong>Concise</strong> — Analysis should be as short as it needs to be and no shorter.
			If a finding requires three paragraphs to explain, it either isn't clear yet or wasn't
			worth finding. Good analysis fits in a headline with supporting evidence.
		</li>
		<li>
			<strong>Transparent</strong> — Sources, assumptions, and limitations are stated plainly.
			Reproducibility is not optional. If someone else can't verify the work, the work isn't finished.
		</li>
		<li>
			<strong>Low Hanging Fruit First</strong> — Always start with the most direct question.
			Counts, sums, averages, and distributions come before clustering, forecasting, or causal
			inference. Complexity is only added when it changes a conclusion.
		</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>What This Is Not</h2>
	<p>
		This is not a machine learning tutorial. It is not a data engineering course. It does not
		cover advanced statistics for its own sake. There are excellent resources for all of those
		things. This project is specifically about the discipline of restraint — of doing less and
		communicating more clearly.
	</p>

	<h2>Who This Is For</h2>
	<p>
		Low Hanging Data is written for anyone who works with data and wants to produce analysis
		that decision-makers actually trust and use:
	</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Analysts</strong> who want their work to have more impact with less overhead.</li>
		<li><strong>Developers</strong> building data features who need to communicate findings to non-technical stakeholders.</li>
		<li><strong>Researchers</strong> who want their methodology to be reproducible and their conclusions defensible.</li>
		<li><strong>Anyone</strong> who has ever been asked "so what does this actually mean?" after presenting data.</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Articles</h2>
	<p>
		The <a href="/blog">Articles</a> section contains practical guides that apply these principles
		to real tasks — pulling data, cleaning it, querying it, and presenting results. Each article
		leads with the simplest viable approach and explains when (and whether) to go further.
	</p>
</Layout>
